  "response": "To get admitted to MIT, you'll need to:\n\n1. Academic Preparation\n- Excel in math and science courses\n- Take advanced/AP classes\n- Maintain a very high GPA (typically 4.0+)\n- Score extremely well on SAT/ACT (median MIT scores are around 1540 SAT)\n\n2. Extracurricular Activities\n- Demonstrate leadership\n- Participate in STEM-related activities\n- Engage in research or competitive academic programs\n- Show passion and achievement in science/technology\n\n3. Strong Application\n- Write compelling essays\n- Get excellent letters of recommendation\n- Highlight unique achievements and innovative projects\n- Show intellectual curiosity and problem-solving skills\n\n4. Application Components\n- Submit MIT application\n- Complete MIT supplemental essays\n- Send standardized test scores\n- Provide detailed academic and extracurricular records\n\n5. Additional Recommendations\n- Participate in math/science competitions\n- Pursue independent research\n- Develop programming or engineering skills\n- Show intellectual creativity\n\n6. Financial Considerations\n- Apply for financial aid\n- Explore scholarship opportunities\n- Consider MIT's need-blind admission policy\n\nRemember, MIT is extremely competitive, accepting less than 7% of applicants annually. Demonstrate exceptional academic and personal qualities.",
